{"questionId":"21953","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>A manufacturer of chocolates produces them in individual packets, claiming to have an&nbsp;average of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>85</mn></math> chocolates per packet.</p>\n<p>Talha bought <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>30</mn></math> of these packets in order to check the manufacturer’s claim.</p>\n<p>Given that the number of individual chocolates is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>, Talha found that, from his <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>30</mn></math> packets,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>Σ</mtext><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2506</mn></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>Σ</mtext><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>209</mn><mo> </mo><mn>738</mn></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Use the formula&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi>s</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mtext>Σ</mtext><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><msup><mfenced><mrow><mtext>Σ</mtext><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>n</mi></mfrac></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac></math> to determine an unbiased estimate for the variance&nbsp;of the number of chocolates per packet.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><msubsup><mi>s</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mtext>Σ</mtext><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><msup><mfenced><mrow><mtext>Σ</mtext><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>n</mi></mfrac></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo></mrow></mfenced><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>209738</mn><mo>-</mo><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><msup><mn>2506</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mn>30</mn></mfrac></mstyle></mrow><mn>29</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>9126</mn><mo>…</mo></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong><br>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"21953","referenceCode":"21M.1.AHL.TZ2.10b","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Use the formula sn-12=Σx2-Σx2nn-1 to determine an unbiased estimate for the variance of the number of chocolates per packet.","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","AHL 4.14—Linear transformation of a single RV, E(X) and VAR(X), unbiased estimators","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","AHL 4.16—Confidence intervals"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}